President of South Africa, Mr Cyril Ramaphosa has apologized to Nigeria over the xenophobic attacks in South Africa. The apology was tendered to  President Muhammadu Buhari in the State House, Abuja by the South Africa special envoys led by Mr Jeff Radabe alongside others despatched to Nigeria over the increasing xenophobic attacks on Nigerians and other Africans living in South Africa.  Mr Radebe apologized on behalf of his President for what he called “acts of criminality and violence” adding that “such do not represent the value system, nor those of the larger number of South Africans.” He said South Africa was an integral part of Africa, and is fully committed to peace and integration of the continent. Our state House Correspondent, Raliat Adenekan reports that the Special Envoy disclosed that 10 people died during the attacks – two Zimbabweans, eight South Africans and there was no Nigerian casualty.  Speaking on Compensation of the victims, Mr Jeff said that discussions  on compensation will be deliberated on during the coming visit of the Nigerian President in October which would further solidify relationship between the two countries.  President Buhari however responded to profuse apologies from the South African President, pledging that relationship between the two countries “will be solidified,” while describing the xenophobic attacks as “very unfortunate.” Meanwhile, the minister of foreign affairs, Mr Geoffery Onyeama reiterated that the Nigerian high commissioner to south african, Kabiru Bala has not been recalled adding that he is here to brief the President further on the situation.